found that I kept winning.

57
00:02:18,660 --> 00:02:21,480
This was probably because I
chose jobs I had an interest in

58
00:02:21,480 --> 00:02:24,217
rather than learning things I
didn't care about at school.

59
00:02:24,217 --> 00:02:26,850
"The Winner Effect" talks
about actual studies

60
00:02:26,850 --> 00:02:28,410
to back up this phenomenon.

61
00:02:28,410 --> 00:02:30,960
The book discusses how
positive correlation

62
00:02:30,960 --> 00:02:33,900
has been found between
successful stock market traders

63
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:35,520
and their testosterone levels.

64
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:38,550
Furthermore winning increases
the testosterone receptors

65
00:02:38,550 --> 00:02:41,820
in your brain which causes
you to win more in the future.

66
00:02:41,820 --> 00:02:44,430
That's why it's important to
set those achievable goals

67
00:02:44,430 --> 00:02:46,680
and get those little wins every day.

68
00:02:46,680 --> 00:02:48,510
I believe that my struggles in school

69
00:02:48,510 --> 00:02:50,220
and my strong drive for success

70
00:02:50,220 --> 00:02:52,500
had a positive impact on my life.

71
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:55,417
They left me with no other
option but to push forward.

72
00:02:55,417 --> 00:02:59,220
"Think and Grow Rich" tells a
story about a great commander.

73
00:02:59,220 --> 00:03:02,400
Despite being outnumbered
by a far superior enemy,

74
00:03:02,400 --> 00:03:04,410
he burned his army's own ships

75
00:03:04,410 --> 00:03:06,270
leaving them with no escape plan.

76
00:03:06,270 --> 00:03:09,360
This forced his soldiers to
fight with everything they had

77
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:12,570
resulting in a miraculous
victory against all the odds.

78
00:03:12,570 --> 00:03:14,580
It just shows there's a big difference

79
00:03:14,580 --> 00:03:18,000
between wanting to succeed and needing to.

80
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,430
Being comfortable is just as harmful

81
00:03:20,430 --> 00:03:22,320
as having an escape plan.

82
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:24,120
During a chat with Andrew Tate,

83
00:03:24,120 --> 00:03:27,037
he referred to this as
one of the matrix's tools.

84
00:03:27,037 --> 00:03:30,240
"Unscripted" also presents this idea.

85
00:03:30,240 --> 00:03:33,330
The author argues that
society aims to transform us

86
00:03:33,330 --> 00:03:36,990
into model citizens,
which stands for mediocre,

87
00:03:36,990 --> 00:03:40,770
obedient, dependent,
entertained and lifeless.

88
00:03:40,770 --> 00:03:42,870
Avoiding this fate depends on how well

89
00:03:42,870 --> 00:03:44,197
you can manage stress.

90
00:03:44,197 --> 00:03:47,730
"The Essence of Success"
gives us a helpful perspective

91
00:03:47,730 --> 00:03:48,563
on this.

92
00:03:48,563 --> 00:03:51,060
The book mentions that all
the water that forms a fog

93
00:03:51,060 --> 00:03:54,240
that's 100 feet deep and
seven city blocks wide

94
00:03:54,240 --> 00:03:56,640
can fit into a small glass.

95
00:03:56,640 --> 00:03:58,890
Whenever I feel stressed I like to imagine

96
00:03:58,890 --> 00:04:01,050
drinking this water and using it as fuel.

97
00:04:01,050 --> 00:04:03,180
Now you can develop great habits.

98
00:04:03,180 --> 00:04:06,900
Stress can also come from
factors outside our control.

99
00:04:06,900 --> 00:04:09,060
For this reason, I've
made a conscious effort

100
00:04:09,060 --> 00:04:11,103
throughout my life to only focus on things

101
00:04:11,103 --> 00:04:13,087
that I can directly impact.

102
00:04:13,087 --> 00:04:16,200
"Atomic Habits" reveals
that many people fixate

103
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:19,440
on the end goal, which
they have no control over

104
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:21,600
rather than a process of achieving it

105
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:23,220
which is completely in their hands.

106
00:04:23,220 --> 00:04:25,380
I found the author's
habit stacking technique

107
00:04:25,380 --> 00:04:28,230
to be particularly helpful
for forming new habits.

108
00:04:28,230 --> 00:04:31,350
It involves pairing a new
habit with an existing one

109
00:04:31,350 --> 00:04:33,480
so both are completed at the same time.

110
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:35,820
However, most people just
keep putting things off

111
00:04:35,820 --> 00:04:37,890
and never form good habits.

112
00:04:37,890 --> 00:04:40,860
I know far too many people
just go through the motions

113
00:04:40,860 --> 00:04:44,400
without any direction
and before they know it,

114
00:04:44,400 --> 00:04:45,337
time has run out.

115
00:04:45,337 --> 00:04:48,090
"The Seven Habits of
Highly Effective People"

116
00:04:48,090 --> 00:04:50,400
stresses the importance of always knowing

117
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:52,050
where you are going and thinking about

118
00:04:52,050 --> 00:04:53,850
how you want to be remembered.

119
00:04:53,850 --> 00:04:56,430
I know this provides me
with extra motivation

120
00:04:56,430 --> 00:04:58,890
but this is only one part of the equation.

121
00:04:58,890 --> 00:05:02,550
The 12 week year suggests
treating a year as 12 weeks

122
00:05:02,550 --> 00:05:04,380
to create a sense of urgency.

123
00:05:04,380 --> 00:05:05,760
This really hit home for me

124
00:05:05,760 --> 00:05:08,340
as I know I work best under pressure.

125
00:05:08,340 --> 00:05:10,860
Although short-term
pain is often necessary

126
00:05:10,860 --> 00:05:13,980
for long-term gain, it can
be difficult to remember this

127
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:15,217
when faced with challenges.

128
00:05:15,217 --> 00:05:18,600
"The Art of Getting Things
Done" emphasizes the importance

129
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:22,140
of not relying on your brain
to remember all your tasks.

130
00:05:22,140 --> 00:05:24,990
Instead, capture them
on a phone or a notepad.

131
00:05:24,990 --> 00:05:26,910
This way you can organize your task

132
00:05:26,910 --> 00:05:28,620
without getting them confused

133
00:05:28,620 --> 00:05:31,477
and you can also be selective
with how you spend your time.

134
00:05:31,477 --> 00:05:35,490
"Essentialism" reminds us that
for every task we say yes to,

135
00:05:35,490 --> 00:05:37,560
we have to say no to many others.

136
00:05:37,560 --> 00:05:39,990
Therefore, it's important to value yes

137
00:05:39,990 --> 00:05:41,970
and not be afraid to say no.

138
00:05:41,970 --> 00:05:43,710
After adopting these habits

139
00:05:43,710 --> 00:05:46,740
you should start building
high value skills.

140
00:05:46,740 --> 00:05:49,350
I've previously said that
I don't like the advice,

141
00:05:49,350 --> 00:05:50,670
follow your passion.

142
00:05:50,670 --> 00:05:52,770
However, "So Good They Can't Ignore You"

143
00:05:52,770 --> 00:05:54,240
takes it one step further.

144
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:57,360
The author interviewed many
people who loved their jobs.

145
00:05:57,360 --> 00:05:59,640
He found that most of
them didn't initially

146
00:05:59,640 --> 00:06:01,230
